Russian President Vladimir Putin signed a law introducing administrative liability for violating the terms and procedures for payment for goods (works, services) when purchasing for state and municipal needs.
This law is designed to solve the very acute problem of the non-fulfillment of their obligations by customers in the implementation of state and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, it was common for entrepreneurs to be unable to receive payment for government and municipal contracts that had already been fulfilled.
At the same time, the President of Russia instructed the General Prosecutor's Office of the Russian Federation to take the problem under special control.
Because businessmen themselves could not cope with unscrupulous customers who concluded contracts not supported by financing, tried to evade their payment obligations and included illegal conditions in contracts.
The problem was systemic across the country.
Since 2015, in the interests of protecting the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment for public orders, the prosecutor's office has made 9,7 thousand representations, according to the results of their consideration, 4,5 thousand officials have been brought to disciplinary responsibility, 533 to administrative, 75 materials have been submitted to the investigative bodies to organize procedural checks, 46 of them have initiated criminal cases.
As a result, debts to entrepreneurs were paid off in the amount of more than 66 billion rubles.
And these vast sums were not accumulated by the non-payment of multibillion-dollar contracts.
The debt was compounded by numerous, systematic delays in paying far more modest sums to entrepreneurs.
Here's a typical case.
The head of a small company won a competition for social transportation services for several million rubles.
A man has invested all his working capital, has fully met his obligations, but has not received the money on time.
The result is a growing financial burden of payroll, tax, credit, which would have led to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur had not sought help from the prosecutor's office.
Now, in some regions, the problem has been brought to a maximum level.
However, as of the first half of 2017, the total debt for state and municipal contracts, as identified by prosecutors of the subjects of the Russian Federation, amounted to about 27.4 billion rubles.
In regions where debt levels continue to reach critical levels, prosecutors are operating in a manual crisis management mode.
The Prosecutor General personally holds on-the-spot meetings with representatives of local authorities, at which all violations discovered by prosecutors and measures for their immediate elimination are examined in detail.
Such operational meetings have already been held in Yaroslavl and Yekaterinburg this year.
The implementation of the Federal Law No. 189-FZ "On Amendments to the Code of the Russian Federation on Administrative Offences in Part of the Establishment of Administrative Responsibility of Officials of the Customer for Violation of the Term and Order of Payment of Goods (Works, Services) in Purchases for the Provision of State and Municipal Needs" which was signed by the President of Russia last week will be able to improve the payment discipline of public customers qualitatively.
The draft law was developed by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia on the initiative of the Prosecutor General's Office.
The new law will supplement the Code of the Russian Federation on Administrative Offences with an article that provides for a fine of 30 thousand to 50 thousand rubles for violation by a customer's official person of the term and procedure for payment of goods, works and services at state and municipal purchases.
If the official has already been subjected to administrative punishment for a similar offence, then he faces disqualification for a period of one to two years.
All prosecutors of the Russian Federation have already received instructions to ensure the application of these legislative novelties in practice.
A civil rights group has issued a travel warning in Missouri.
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a travel warning for people of color in Missouri because of the state's discriminatory policies and racially motivated attacks.
The group's statement reads: "The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People's Travel Warning, effective until August 28, 2017, calls on African-American travelers, visitors, and citizens of the state of Missouri to be especially careful and exercise heightened caution when traveling in the state due to a number of suspicious racist incidents that have recently occurred throughout the state and here".
According to the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, the group's move to issue a travel warning was prompted by a recent Missouri law that made it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, and by the fact that state law enforcement agencies disproportionately target minorities.
You have people being subjected to human rights abuses.
They're being stopped on the roads because of their skin color, they're being beaten and killed", said Rod Chapel, president of the Missouri Association for the Advancement of Colored People, to the Kansas City Star.
We hear complaints more often than ever before.
This is the first such warning issued by the organization against a U.S. state.
The group cited incidents such as the racially discriminated humiliation of black students at the University of Missouri and the death of 28-year-old Tory Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died under suspicious circumstances earlier this year after running out of gas on a state trip, and Missouri State Police arrested him without charge of a crime.
The warning also cites a recent report from the Missouri Attorney General's Office, which found that black drivers are 75 percent more likely to be stopped on the road than white drivers.
"The purpose of the alert is to make people aware of the situation and warn their relatives and friends and colleagues about what could happen in Missouri", Chappell said.
"People should be prepared one way or another, whether they're taking money for a deposit or telling relatives they're traveling across state lines".
According to the latest data from the FBI's Hate Crime Reporting Program, Missouri had 100 hate crimes in 2015, making it the 16th largest state in the nation for hate crimes.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that makes it harder to prosecute a business for housing or employment discrimination.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) earlier issued travel warnings for Texas and Arizona after those states passed new immigration control laws that ordered local law enforcement to arrest people for violating immigration laws, which the ACLU said would increase racial screening.
Travel warnings are typically issued by the State Department in relation to other countries, but more recently, civil society organizations have resorted to this measure in response to certain laws and trends within the United States.
