Nothing sacred about it?
Now the Trump White House is targeting the Statue of Liberty.
The most certain sign of a regime change is when he starts fighting the statues.
The Americans know this as well as anyone else, hence the deliberate theatrical demolition of Saddam Hussein's statue in Firdous Square in Baghdad in 2003.
Steven Miller, one of the key ideologues in the Trump administration, no doubt knew what he was doing when he brought the symbolic axe to the Statue of Liberty during a heated debate with CNN journalist Jim Akosta about the president's proposals for a sharp reduction in legal immigration.
Let's face it, Miller didn't try to kill the statue.
A dozen boat owners and artists who painted the Statue of Liberty would have him lynched if he tried.
But he did attack its meaning, and particularly the meaning that was attributed to it in 1903, 17 years after the monument was completed, when the poems of Emma Lazarus were added to the pedestal.
As Miller grumbled to Acosta, "I don't want to go too deep into history here, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that illuminates the world.
The poem you're referring to was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty".
Miller's account of the facts is correct, but as he said, it's not really about the story.
It's about the current sound of Lazarus's astonishing words, the only ones in which the state invites not just any immigrants, but the poorest: "Your weary, your poor, / your crowds dreaming to breathe freely, / Miserable wastes of your abundant shores".
Never before has "unfortunate waste" been so prominent on our screens.
Miller wasn't a literary scholar, he was making it clear that Trump's America was not waiting for these people.
This debate about the meaning of the statue is part of a larger political and cultural war: it's really a debate about the meaning of America.
Lazarus and her friends, who fought to have her words placed on the base of the statue after her death, were well aware that they were committing a purely political act.
The sculpture was intended to represent the link between the French and American republics through the banal classic figure of the female image of Liberty.
Lazarus changed its meaning: in her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract, she has a voice.
And she got a whole new name: Mother of the Banished.
The marriage of poem and image was a brilliant feminist move and a crushing attack on American nativism.
And how Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, right though to change it back.
The loud-voiced Rush Limbaugh, a sort of John the Baptist who heralded Trump's arrival, argued in 2010 that Liberty is not inviting, but rather an early neocon bearing America's flame to a world in darkness: "Freedom is moving forward.
She carries the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch is not to light the way to the United States".
Against the grain, Limbo really got a point.
The meaning of the statue depends entirely on the angle of view.
The great creative achievement of Lazarus was to see her as she would be seen by the tired, unhappy, but hopeful men on the decks of ships after a long and often arduous voyage.
It means literally looking at the world through the eyes of people who are seeking refuge and a chance for a better life.
Her statue is responding to them with the words of hope and hospitality they've been longing to hear.
And that's certainly not a perspective that Miller and Trump would ever want to embrace.
Their torch is not to light the way, but to fan the flames of hatred, which is the only source of their power.
