Blocking critics on Facebook: Don't run for public office unless you're ready to hear criticism from voters
The founding father of our country understood the critical press.
Americans loved George Washington, but that didn't stop them from criticizing him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
The criticism, of course, annoyed him.
But he did not silence his critics.
Because back in 1783, Washington said, "You can take away free speech, and we, the deaf and dumb, will be led like sheep to the slaughter".
I'm going to go now to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who should be trying to be more like Washington.
Hogan's employees have blocked and deleted posts from at least 450 people who expressed their opinions on his official Facebook page.
And this week, the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for it.
The governor's subordinates called the lawsuit trivial, and the comment on the Internet was written in the spirit of "what if".
"It's just Facebook", many people would say.
But this is important, too.
And that's especially important when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He's a surprisingly popular Republican governor in a predominantly Democratic state.
He's second in the approval ratings of the 50 governors in the country.
Hogan is not a stubborn reactionary.
He has demonstrated a firm hand in the governance of the state and a commitment to his principles.
He also cleverly uses Facebook as his primary means of communication with his constituents and jokingly shows off his bald head from chemotherapy on his page.
So blocking people from coming to the governor's website - which is billed as an official public forum and run by the administration staff at taxpayer dollars - is unnecessary and ultimately harmful.
In an interview with the Washington Post, spokeswoman Amelia Ches defended the governor's actions, arguing that blocking comments was simply moderating them.
But it's too easy to use the image of trolls, spammers and haters to perpetrate online mischief.
The Post talked to some of the real people that Hogan's blocked.
And these are real people, not trolls, teachers, businessmen, pastors, who are addressing their elected leaders.
All of them say their comments were respectful, meaningful and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible, appealing to Hogan's Catholicism.
Attorney Lakshmi Sarma Raman of Bowie, Maryland, did not express hatred, but asked about hate crimes.
"I wrote a polite comment about how disappointed I was by his lack of reaction to hate crimes and other recent news", she wrote in the Post comment section.
"I also don't like the idea that when a lot of people leave comments on the same topic, some of them immediately say it's a so-called hoax instead of admitting that they are dealing with a large group of disgruntled citizens".
What the governor's subordinates call a "concentrated spam attack", others would probably call an "active life position".
In the Facebook era, it's easy to edit your image by simply blocking critics or deleting negative comments.
It's a lot less dusty work than it used to be, when it required sending people out, collecting and burning critical newspapers or arresting and silencing protesters.
But that's exactly what's happening now, just in numbers.
Hogan is not the first official to be criticized for not wanting to listen to Facebook and other social networks.
President Trump was sued by Twitter users who were banned from his Twitter account.
One of the first, the first, the first major decisions on this issue was made this week in Virginia.
According to Alexandria U.S. District Judge James K. Casher, the chairman of the Loudoun County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment by banning a voter from her Facebook account.
And in Kentucky, Republican Governor Matt Bavin was sued by the American Civil Liberties Union for his behavior on Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington's day, the era of affordable postage was about as revolutionary as the Internet is today.
From 1776 to 1800, newspapers quadrupled in number, and anonymous letter writers greatly undermined its authority.
And even then, Washington was dealing with anonymous trolls.
People using the names "Uricula", "Valerius", "Belisarius", and "Porcius" wrote letters to newspapers mocking Washington's decision.
According to historical documents collected by the online project George Washington Papers, his office was flooded with petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty of Amity, Commerce and Navigation.
But he didn't try to shut them up.
Freedom of speech, of opinion and expression is the foundation of our state.
And true leadership means agreeing to it.
