Poverty and death in the Indonesian 'golden land'
While preparing lunch, the Barden of the Degeys does not use the stove.
She rarely even uses a pickle.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of Paniai district in the rebellious Indonesian province of Papua, a housewife usually just puts a sweet potato, which is called notata here, right in the fireplace.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is pulled out and eaten with impatient, unwashed hands.
DeGeis sits on the dirt floor - she has no furniture - and it is here that she does her household chores, such as washing clothes with muddy water from a nearby swamp.
The bathroom is a bucket in a room with no roof.
She was the youngest of her husband's four wives, and so she was not assigned to work in the fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: many men in this village are unemployed, many drink, and there are soldiers.
"No one dares to walk around the village after five in the evening", she says.
It's a rare glimpse into daily life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a questionable referendum, when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote by publicly raising their hands in front of the occupying troops.
The existing movement for independence from the Netherlands quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta government, which maintains tight control over the region, barring foreign journalists and human rights activists.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, with the independent state of Papua New Guinea occupying the eastern part of the island.
Etaru is as remote as it is deserted; the journey here involves a one-and-a-half-hour flight from Jaipur, the provincial capital, to Nabir, followed by a five-hour shake-up in a hired car.
There's no public transportation around here.
The town of about 19,000 people is made up of wooden houses with bamboo fences; the roofs are made of corrugated steel and painted with rust in various reddish hues.
Few Indonesians have ever been here, let alone journalists, and hardly any foreigners.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the Me'e Pago worshiped a deity called U'ga Tame'e.
There were other changes.
"We were not used to wearing these clothes", Degeye says, pointing to his bright hand-woven turban, dark skirt and brightly colored shirt.
We used to wear only leaves on our bodies.
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line, and its infant mortality and literacy rates are among the worst in Asia.
