In addition, Papua boasts forest reserves estimated at $78 billion.
These riches, however, bring one misfortune to the Papuans, ensuring that Indonesia's powerful military maintains its suffocating presence here.
According to a 2005 New York Times investigation, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid nearly $20 million to local military personnel and units, including up to $150,000 to one officer.
The demands for greater autonomy from the Papuans threaten the existence of this golden vein and are ruthlessly suppressed.
Since 1969, human rights activists say, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by Indonesian military forces, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, the mass killings of indigenous people in the highlands of Papua in the 1970s can be considered genocide.
Last year alone, police in Indonesia arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
We will lose everything, a report published in 2016 by the Diocese of Brisbane, contains evidence of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as executions without trial, torture  especially frequent, as claimed in another report, rape and electrocution  and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
It is difficult to count the number of victims because the incidents happen every week, says Andreas Harsono, a researcher in Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
The geysers have been drawn in as Papua's resources have attracted an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
The province's 3.5 million population is 83% Christian, but demographic indicators are changing as Muslim economic migrants arrive from the densely populated Indonesian islands of Java, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
The Javanese shop, varunggi, sells fried chicken and a vegetable mixture gado-gado, served with peanut sauce.
The locals are trying to survive the competition.
"Migrants started selling chicken and vegetables at the traditional market for cheaper prices than the native Papuans", explains Abet Yoo, a 24-year-old from Paniai who moved to Jayapura, the provincial capital, for work.
 Because of this, the indigenous Papuans  the Papuans' mama-mama (women)  have lost their market.
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, vowed to tackle inequality and rights abuses in Papua during his 2014 presidential campaign.
On his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta, the former carpenter enlisted the support of 27 of Papua's 29 districts, including Paniai.
But in Papua, little has changed, and the locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Djokovic, expecting him to fulfill our hopes for restoring justice", Yow says.
In reality, just two months after the October inauguration of Jokowi, Paniai suffered a tragedy.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were outside singing Christmas carols at a bonfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on motorcycles escaped from the darkness.
Frightened children told them to turn on their lights.
According to local pastor Javed Tebai, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone and returned with four soldiers after a while.
According to victims and witnesses, the soldiers, who were drunk, chased the children and beat them with rifle butts.
Then one of the soldiers fired at a group of children.
One of the children, 16-year-old Julianus Aimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to the nearby government election commission building, and the next day, things got worse.
About a thousand Papuan men, women and children gathered on a football pitch in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They brought with them ritual hunting bows and performed the vayta, a dance of the Papuas tribe me'e'ago: they ran in circles and imitated the birdsong.
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police station and the military base.
When the situation escalated, soldiers were given an internal radio order: "If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them", according to an official document seen by TIME magazine, but not published in local media.
Fifty-six-year-old Jeremiah Kayame, the head of the Kego Koto district in Enoratali, sensed the approaching danger and called for calm, asking the crowd to disperse to their homes.
No one wanted to listen to him.
"When I turned around, I suddenly got a bullet in my left wrist", he told TIME magazine, standing on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who fired the shot, but says the bullet came from a line of soldiers.
"There was a crowd, there was a lot of gunfire", he added.
Local resident Alfius Yow was shot three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting.
"I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him", Johannes, who, like many Indonesians, has only one name, told TIME.
I saw he was dead... I kissed him.
General Yotje Mende, the chief inspector of the Papua Police, told reporters that his officers were only "defending" their base because it was under attack.
"We must defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us", Papua police spokesman Commissioner Pujo Sulithio said in 2015.
It's a matter of life and death.
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more were injured.
News of the murders did not reach Jakarta until the next day.
Three weeks later, in Jaipur, Jokowi delivered a fiery speech in which he offered condolences to the families of the victims and vowed to address the issue of historical abuses of power in Papua.
"I want this situation to be resolved immediately so that it never happens again in the future", he said.
In October 2016, Security Minister Viranto said he would establish a non-judicial organization to put an end to historical human rights violations.
But almost immediately, there were excuses.
Most of the violations happened a long time ago.
Some of them took place in the nineties or early '90s.
The fact is that we certainly want to deal with these violations, but there are procedures that need to be followed", he said.
Viranto then retracted his comments, speaking to TIME magazine on June 5 in Jakarta, and said he had no plans to establish a complaints body in Papua.
Instead, he said, "Everything will be decided in a court of law".
Viranto, who was charged by the United Nations with "crimes against humanity" in connection with the deaths of more than 1,000 people during the bloody East Timorese independence vote in 1999, said 11 cases of human rights abuses in Papua had already been addressed, including the Paniai incident.
The families of the Paniai victims have met such statements with grim suspicion.
'I have been interrogated four times in the last three years, but there has been no change at all,' says Johannes.
I'm tired of it.
He says that years later, he still lives in fear.
"I'm scared", he says.
I'm afraid I'll be arrested by the military, I'm afraid I'll be shot.
His brother Jacobus also expressed the opinion that the people of Paniayi are afraid to discuss the incident.
