"We were in such a panic, we were afraid of retaliation", Dominggu Badia, a 29-year-old who lives near the hospital and saw the hurried transport of the wounded, told TIME magazine.
I hid in my house for two days.
Deia demanded that the officers involved be brought to justice and that the mobile police brigade be withdrawn from the area.
Paniai has always been a sick place for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development is a source of discontent among the Me'e, Moni, Dani and Dama tribes scattered throughout the verdant central highlands of Papua.
Many have joined the Free Papua Movement (OPM), a rebel army that claims to defend the rights of the Papuans by carrying out sporadic attacks and kidnapping raids on Indonesian soldiers.
Some of OPM's top executives are from Paniai, including Thadius Yogi and Daniel Judas Kogoya.
In retaliation, in recent years, thousands of people in Paniai have been arrested and detained without charge by the military under the pretext of "protecting national independence".
Some of them never came back.
Among the people of Papua, Paniai is considered a "sad, forgotten place".
Poverty increases discontent.
A small portion of rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for the locals.
