The people here grow everything they eat: mostly walnuts, but also some fruits and leafy vegetables.
Agriculture is the work of women, each of whom can tend four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
They usually keep most of the crop for the family, and sell the rest at the local market.
Ten notes of the club are worth only 10,000 Indonesian rupiahs (75 cents).
Over time, economic inequality increased between the native Papuans and the new migrants, who arrived in large numbers after the introduction of new flights to Nabire airport.
The few available jobs are usually filled by more educated and well-off migrants.
Papuan people rarely have the money or the skills to run their own competitive businesses.
"Young people don't want to stay in the village... because there is no work and no money", says John Gobay, chairman of the Paniai Tribal Council.
Isolation keeps Papua out of the eyes of the rest of the world.
In addition, restrictions on international media remain severe.
Earlier this year, French journalists Franck Escudie and Basile Longchamp were deported from Papua for "not coordinating with the relevant organizations" despite being issued rare video permits.
According to Felim Keen, deputy Asia director of Human Rights Watch, promises made during the election campaign by Djokovic to lift restrictions on media in order to promote transparency and development have not been fulfilled.
"Now, foreign journalists trying to report from Indonesia's rebellious eastern provinces, Papua and West Papua, face new dangers: visa denials and blacklisting", he said in a statement.
The lack of press coverage means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is largely confined to Papua's immediate neighbors.
In March, six Pacific nations - Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and the Solomon Islands - asked the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "the diverse and widespread violations" in Papua, including the shootings in Paniai.
