The screaming broke the silence as the young black man was dragged from the front seat.
Fortunately, the terrible scene that took place on July 22 was only a staged event.
But when Roger was put on the noose, almost everyone in the audience was breathless.
Since 2005, activists have returned to the Morse Ford Bridge to re-enact the night in 1946 when the Ku Klux Klan lynched two black couples - Roger and Dorothy Malcolm and George and May Murray Dorsey.
No one was convicted of these murders.
"It's amazing that in all these years, not one person has been arrested - even though we see them around us; even though we know who they are", says Tyrone Brooks, who helped organize the production.
"It's a stain on our history and it's a stone on our souls".
Brooks, 71, is a former congressman from Georgia who has spent his life fighting for human rights.
For him, the play is a dramatic call to action and an annual reminder to the residents of Monroe that the injustice has never been corrected.
"We want investigations, we want closures, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we have to get justice", he says.
"We cannot move toward healing and reconciliation until we achieve justice".
A coroner covers the plain body of one of the victims of the Morse Ford lynching on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI files obtained by NBC News, more than 50 people in Monroe and neighboring counties were suspected of involvement in the lynching.
But no one was ever charged.
Although the suspects have been at large for decades, human rights activists say the city has always been well aware of two related motives for lynching: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court ruling allowed black citizens to vote for the first time in the primaries that were to be held that summer.
Around the same election, the FBI reported that black exploiter Roger Malcolm stabbed Barnett Hester, a white landowner, in a brawl, apparently over a woman.
Brooks says that rumors were spreading in town that Hester was sleeping with Malcolm's wife Dorothy, and that the child she was going to have was not from her husband.
According to FBI records, on July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a large white landowner, paid $600 in bail to get Malcolm out of prison.
He went to prison with Dorothy and their cousins, May Murray and George Dorsey.
But as they were driving from the prison to the Morse Ford Bridge, a mob of lynch mobs surrounded the car.
"It appears that Harrison organized and ordered the murders", concludes one FBI report.
"It is also clear that there was collusion between state and city law enforcement, "which not only participated in the murders, "but also destroyed evidence and concealed the identities of witnesses".
Brooks calls it a shortcut.
"It was an attempt to invade voting rights", he says.
"They were all killed to send a message to the black people in the city that if you register and vote, the same thing will happen to you".
For nearly a decade, Cassandra Green has been running the annual show recreating the lynching at the Morse Ford Bridge.
Her performance is vivid, it's engaging, and it's about the deep racism that many would like to think is no longer in America.
He's hard to look at, and even harder to turn away from, but Green thinks that's what's important.
"We don't want to talk about the Lynch trials because they show us our own ugliness", she says.
"But I can't have a relationship with you if you don't hear me or hear what I've been through".
Rehearsals for this year's production began in June, and on the first day, nearly 30 actors - a dozen white, the rest black - gathered in the room and listened to the play's polished review over the years.
Wade Marbeau was the director with Greene.
He's played the role of the clan's head for a few years, but he says the role hasn't gotten any easier.
"I feel like I've been soiled because that's not who I am", says Marbaud.
"But I think it's very important to remember that story, because we don't want to go back to that time".
In the room, actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, who play Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hester, are re-enacting their roles.
The play begins with Malcolm, angry that Hester is sleeping with his wife Dorothy, yelling and pushing him.
"I said, nigga, get out of my house!"
Rascona shouts back.
The shot is fired.
And at the same time, everyone (at least all black actors) is laughing.
Green laughs the loudest.
"What is it?" asked Ascona.
He's worried and confused.
Am I being too forward?
"No", Green says through a laugh.
"I just don't think white people used to say 'nigga' back then".
"Yeah, yeah", one of the black performers laughs.
"You must rise to the solid 'r'".
And so the energy in the room changes, the discomfort is replaced by a sense of camaraderie.
Everyone has to do the right thing, not just for the sake of the play, but for the sake of the memory of the four people who were killed.
The scene starts again.
This time, when Rascona says the "N" word, it comes out sharp and clear.
No man is laughing.
The show ends violently and quickly.
Screams, shots, and then silence.
A woman in black mourning clothes stands over the bodies of the actors and sings the sad song "Strange Fruit" by Billie Holiday.
Her voice is broken by a word.
A hundred yards away, half a hundred spectators are wiping tears and sweat from their eyes.
There's almost an equal number of blacks and whites in the audience.
One couple came from Ithaca, New York, to see the show; many live just a block away.
They all endured the heavy Georgia breeze for almost eight hours while Brooks led them on a pilgrimage to the graves of the Malcolm and Dorsey.
Before that, the murders were history, but now, as they stand in the same place where they lynched people, it seems like their ghosts are in the air.
As the song's final note falls, Green invites the crowd to come closer and examine the bodies.
The children lean over their heads, touch the paint that represents blood and the immobile bodies, and whisper something to each other.
"They're not really dead", one little boy mutters, as if to remind himself of it.
A few minutes later, Green thanks the audience, and then it's over.
Actors take the ropes off their necks and wipe their tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbo, the man in the suit who played the main puppet worshipper.
Nick Rascona hugs the other two actors and then, crying, falls into their arms: the emotional burden of the play has finally fallen on him.
"It's all right", one of the women whispers.
"We know your heart is good.
You had your reasons".
Later, the audience sits down to dinner with the actors.
At one table, a white couple from Atlanta are having a lively discussion about a play with a black couple they've just met.
Deniza Daplinsky has a hard time finding the words to describe what she feels after the play.
"It's hard to listen to these horrible, creepy words, and actions... of people who look like you, and who do it because they look like you", she says.
"After that, I think lynchings still happen", she adds, "but now it's called police shooting".
In the other corner of the room, the focus is on Tyrone Brooks, as he recalls his work as a human rights activist over a meal.
He says he's already started planning next year's show.
"The play inspires us because it not only describes the horror of what we went through, but it also teaches us", he says.
"Because if you don't learn from this, it could happen again.
Those who do not study their history, who do not know their history, are doomed to repeat it".
