New test results for asylum seekers' age assessment in Sweden published
The latest test results of asylum seekers in Sweden who underwent a new medical age assessment method show that more than 80 percent of those tested were assessed as over the age of 18, but not everyone trusts the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish National Agency for Forensic Medicine (Rättsmedicinalverket) started testing earlier this year.
They were designed to make the age estimation in the asylum process more accurate, after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticized for failing to determine the true age of some refugees who claimed to be minors.
So far, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of 2,481 tests for the period between mid-March and 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) of the test subjects were rated as 18 years or older, and in 25 cases the forensic medicine agency rated the test subjects as "likely to be 18 years or older".
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person was probably under 18.
Tests are only carried out when the age of the person is questionable.
According to Johan Göransson of the forensic medicine agency, the results are consistent with those of previous months.
"We don't see much difference with the statistics from the previous months, the numbers are quite appropriate", he told The Local.
The high proportion of cases where people are assessed as over 18 years old does not necessarily indicate that asylum seekers are lying about their age.
In May, the agency released the results of 581 tests and reported that in 442 cases, "the most likely age of the test subject is 18 or older".
However, after reviewing 581 published results, Svenska Dagbladet found that in 243 cases the person openly stated that he would turn 18 this year.
The method of medical age assessment, which consists of taking x-rays of wisdom teeth and tomography of knee joints and giving them to dentists and radiologists for analysis, has also been criticized in some instances.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at the Karolinska Institute, whose part of the job is to assess people's biological maturity to determine whether they've gone through puberty earlier or later than usual.
I had reasons to think about it, and I don't think we should use the measurement methods that we use now.
Biological age is very inaccurate.
If we can't pin it down with certainty, we shouldn't pretend we can", he told Metro.
However, Göranssen of the Forensic Medicine Agency spoke in favor of the accuracy of the tests: "In general, we can say that the risk of mistaking a child for an adult is small.
The biggest risk we face is when a person is about to turn 18, in this case, about 10 percent.
