The president will determine the order and place of swearing in
Where and how new Russian citizens will swear allegiance to the Russian Federation will be determined by the president - such amendments to the second reading of the relevant law were developed by the State Duma Committee on Legislation and State Construction.
A week ago, the lawmakers were planning to directly define the oath-taking process in the law.
Children under 18 years of age, as well as those who are incapable, will be exempted from taking the solemn oath, according to the draft amendments to the draft law "On citizenship of the Russian Federation" (which is in the possession of "Izvestia"), which the committee will consider before the second reading at its meeting on July 11.
The idea of introducing an oath when entering Russian citizenship instead of formally signing documents was supported by President Vladimir Putin on June 6 during a meeting with State Duma Speaker Vyacheslav Volodin.
The deputies formalized this idea in the form of an amendment to the second reading in a bill that would repeal the decision to grant citizenship to those who were subsequently convicted of a number of crimes of a terrorist or extremist nature: for example, for public calls for terrorism or its public justification in the media or on the Internet (No. 2 of Art. 205.2 of the RF Criminal Code), as well as for hijacking an aircraft, train or water transport, but only if this act is related to terrorism (No. 4 of Art. 211 of the RF Criminal Code).
According to the bill, its logic was that by issuing citizenship documents, a person signed a promise to abide by Russian law - by taking the path of extremism, he violates this promise.
The bill was introduced in the State Duma in April by the leaders of the Duma factions Vladimir Vasilyev ("United Russia"), Gennady Zyuganov (KPRF), Vladimir Zhirinovsky (LDPR), Sergey Mironov ("Fair Russia") and the speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
On May 19, the deputies passed it in the first reading.
Last week, the State Duma Committee on State Construction and Legislation approved the text of the bill for the second reading, but now it has been reworked again.
Now it says that the order of swearing in will be established by the President of the Russian Federation.
Earlier, parliamentarians were going to describe the procedure directly in the law "On citizenship of the Russian Federation", indicating that the ceremony should be held in a solemn atmosphere in front of the state emblem and flag of Russia in the presence of a representative of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
However, the text of the bill did not make it clear where such an event should take place - the list of places where the emblem of the Russian Federation can be placed is regulated by the corresponding federal constitutional law.
These include courts, offices of heads of state authorities, municipalities, judges, prosecutors, heads of federal executive authorities, etc.
Most likely, it could be the Zags.
Those wishing to become Russian citizens will take the oath after the officials have checked their documents.
But a Russian passport will be issued only after taking an oath, according to the revised text.
A week ago, the bill said that the oath must precede the signing of the decree.
The updated text says that Russians will be sworn in at 18, not 14.
The rule was retained that the inability or limited capacity, as well as those who cannot pronounce, read or sign the text of the oath by hand, will be exempt from taking the oath.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to exempt from this procedure "other persons",
Also, the updated bill prescribes a special procedure for the admission of Ukrainian residents who are considered native speakers of the Russian language.
They will have to officially renounce Ukrainian citizenship by submitting a corresponding application to the competent authority of Ukraine.
A notarized copy of the statement will need to be passed to Russian officials.
The renunciation of "foreign" citizenship, as it is now, will not be required if it is provided for by an international treaty or if it is impossible "for reasons beyond the person's control".
The corresponding amendment to the law was proposed by a group of deputies, among whom were the first vice-speaker of the State Duma Ivan Melnikov (KPRF), Natalia Poklonskaya, Pavel Krasheninnikov and Ayrat Farrakhov (all - "United Russia").
I think many of you know that getting a letter from Ukraine is unrealistic, impossible.
Accordingly, many people are waiting for their fate to be decided on the issue of citizenship of the Russian Federation, - explained the head of the State Committee on State Construction and Legislation Pavel Krashennikov (ER).
In addition, the text clarified that restrictions on the occupation of certain positions for foreigners will not apply to those who have written a letter refusing "other" citizenship and surrendered a previous passport to the Ministry of Internal Affairs of Russia, but "for reasons beyond its control" did not cease to consider him a citizen of another country.
Now foreigners are banned from holding positions in the municipal service, from being employed in facilities and organizations whose activities are related to ensuring Russia's security.
Also, a person with dual citizenship or residence permit of another country cannot become a deputy of the State Duma or a member of the Federation Council.
The law is expected to take effect on September 1, 2017, by which time the necessary bylaws should be in place.
