The Bank of England will keep interest rates at 0.25%
The Bank of England is expected to announce later that interest rates will remain unchanged after weak economic growth and weakening inflation have put to rest rumors of a possible hike.
The Bank of England has warned that economic growth will remain static, and has left interest rates unchanged amid growing pressure on household incomes.
The bank's Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) voted 6-2 to keep rates at 0.25%, with fewer committee members voting for a rate increase this month because weak economic growth has weakened support for a rate increase.
In its quarterly inflation report, the bank capped its forecasts at 1.7% in 2017 and 1.6% in 2018 and warned that the pressure on household incomes would continue, while inflation is still expected to rise to around 3% in the autumn.
However, the bank warned that rate hikes over the next few years would be necessary to control Brexit-induced inflation, and said that borrowing costs would likely have to rise more than expected in financial markets.
The committee also voted to abandon part of a massive package of economic development measures launched a year ago in the wake of Brexit.
Starting next February, the bank will close its emergency funding plan, under which it provides banks with cheap loans, although it has said it now has to provide another 15 billion pounds  to 115 billion pounds under this plan.
In the rate decision minutes, the bank said: "According to the MPC's main forecasts, gross domestic product (GDP) growth will remain sluggish for the foreseeable future, while the pressure on real household incomes continues to affect consumption".
On the issue of rates, he reiterated that in order to stop inflation it would require "some tightening of fiscal policy" to an extent "slightly greater" than the markets expected.
Right now, the markets are predicting the first rise in the third quarter of next year and another one in 2020.
But the bank stressed that all raises would be "gradual" and "limited".
The bank's forecasts for growth this year and next are lower than the forecasts made in May, which were 1.9% and 1.7%.
The bank has left its forecast unchanged at 1.8% in 2018.
Since this news, sterling has fallen against the dollar and the euro.
The pound fell 0.5% to $1.31 and 0.4% to €1.11.
The decision not to change the rate was made after recent disappointing growth figures had dampened the rising expectation of a rise; GDP then grew by 0.3% in the second quarter against 0.2% in the previous three months.
According to the bank's representative, growth is likely to remain at 0.3% in the third quarter, although it will start to increase slightly towards the end of the year.
The bank's latest inflation report has given little cause for joy to households hit by high inflation and very small wage increases, which the bank says will increase before declining.
The bank added that fiscal policy could not prevent a pay shock in the next few years, but it expected wages to recover significantly by the end of its three-year forecast.
The economy is also set to grow as a result of rising demand for British goods, driven by a low pound exchange rate that is offsetting some of the lower consumer spending.
The decision comes a year after rates were cut to 0.25% last August following the shock results of the referendum on leaving the European Union, which saw the pound plunge.
The bank estimates it will likely take four years to have a full impact on prices and the economy.
Before the bank made its final decision on rates, there was a growing buzz around the alleged rate hike as inflation increasingly put pressure on already-stressed households: three members of the panel asked for a 0.5% rate hike in July.
Inflation fell to 2.6% last month from 2.9% in July, though the bank said it was expected and would be offset again in the coming months.
The bank said the higher figure compared to the planned 2% was entirely due to the low pound rate.
