State health service to prescribe controversial HIV drug to 10,000 people
Starting in September, patients will have access to a revolutionary HIV prevention drug after a battle in the High Court over the drug's funding from the NHS.
England's National Health Service has announced that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP), a pill taken before sex that has been shown to reduce the risk of infection in those at risk by an average of 86 percent, will now be provided by the NHS to approximately 10,000 people over an initial three-year trial period.
She agreed to fund the trial after an appeals court upheld a High Court ruling last year that the NHS had the power to pay for the PHE despite her claims that it should be funded by local authorities.
The move, announced on Thursday, was called a "major innovation" by Simon Stevens, the head of England's National Health Service, and a "turning point" by the National Aids Control Agency (NAT).
Before the full roll-out across England by April 2018, venereal clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start enrolling people, with more clinics joining the programme in October.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a course of HIV medication taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV infection in people at high risk.
Taking PrEP before sex is enough of a certain drug to prevent HIV infection.
These drugs can be taken daily or at least two hours before sex.
Patients eligible for treatment include gay and bisexual men, transgender men, and people whose partners are HIV positive and not receiving successful treatment.
Dispensaries will select eligible participants who have agreed to participate in the study, including men, women, transgender people, and individuals whose partners are not known to be HIV-constrained by antiretroviral therapy.
People living and registered with a GP in England will also be able to apply for a potential place at the nearest venereology clinic participating in the programme.
The programme will cost £10 million, and the NHS in England signed a contract to supply the drug this week after an international tender.
The study is designed to assess the full potential of PrEP by collecting clinical data on who is the target audience for the drug, its absorbability and its large-scale use.
This major innovation should complement and reinforce the large-scale and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It's another milestone in more than three decades of progress against one of the biggest health threats facing humanity.
Deborah Gold, president of NAT (National AIDS Control Agency), said: "This is a watershed moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if it's targeted properly at people who are vulnerable and need it, could be a game changer for the HIV epidemic in England.
Starting in September, people at risk for HIV, thanks to this study funded by the National Health Service in England, will have access to a new, groundbreaking drug that can be administered by the individual without consulting a partner, which will lead to the improvement of many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this news.
Ian Green, president of the Terrence Higgins Foundation, said: "The first thing we need to do now is make sure that the trial is rolled out across the country quickly and that no one in the high-risk group for HIV is left behind.
Now that we have the experimental PrEP, we're on our way to protecting over 10,000 people who are at risk for HIV.
Shadow Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: "We very much welcome the start of the PEP trial, which has been delayed by months of delays and delays by the government".
This data demonstrates how revolutionary this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending the transmission of this fatal infection.
This test will take us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PRP.
Now, it's important that the trial be rolled out across the country as soon as possible to protect those at risk of HIV and to take us one step further towards stopping the spread of HIV in our society.
