Judges are offered protection from chairmen .
The Presidential Council for Human Rights (PCHR) on the instructions of Vladimir Putin has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judicial branch of power.
The ECHR proposes to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts and introduce their electiveness.
For the courts of appeal and cassation instances, the HRC wants to introduce special districts that will not be tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court must also submit its proposals within the framework of the presidential mandate.
The HRC has completed the development of proposals that will strengthen the independence of the Russian judiciary.
This work was carried out by the HRC on the instructions of Vladimir Putin of January 3, 2017, which the president gave after a meeting with the members of the council.
At the meeting with the members of the Council on 8 December 2016, there were also some cases of judicial arbitrariness, as well as problems of public control in places of detention of citizens (see "Ъ" on 9 December).
The result of the work of the HRC was 25 proposals that concern both the issues of ensuring the independence of judges and identifying judicial errors, as well as the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of Kremlin human rights defenders is to limit the powers of the court presidents to increase the independence of the other judges.
If a candidate for a judgeship successfully passes the competition and receives the support of the judicial community, the court president, in the opinion of the HRC, should propose him for appointment, without having the right to refuse, as the law now allows.
It is also proposed to deprive the chairman of the right to allocate cases for consideration among judges.
Experts believe that a computer program designed specifically for this purpose can do this.
The ECHR also considers that the chairman has no right to "predetermine the results of the qualification assessment of the judge, initiate his disciplinary action, make decisions on the establishment of additional material payments".
The presidential council considers it necessary to move to "election of the presidents of the courts by the judges themselves" and "to entrust them with powers for a relatively short period with mandatory rotation".
Now all the chairmen of the courts (from republican to district) are appointed for six years by the president on the proposal of the chairman of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
To protect judges from pressure from regional administrations, the HRC proposes to reorganize the appeal and cassation in the courts of general jurisdiction.
Now their structure is tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The ECHR says that "it is necessary to ensure the organization of separate courts of appeal and cassation instances not at the level of regional judicial bodies in the subjects of the Russian Federation, but in judicial districts".
The experts are based on the practice of arbitration courts.
They have "court districts", which do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but guarantee a greater independence from regional officials, who have difficulty using "telephone law".
The HRC proposes that the number of lay judges be increased by the number of people's juries, so that they can handle certain "categories of civil and administrative cases".
For example, about the loss of parental rights, about reinstatement in the workplace, about the protection of honor and dignity, about the loss of driving rights, etc.
"These are just our proposals", - explained to "Kommersant" the member of the Human Rights Committee, the judge of the Constitutional Court in resignation Tamara Morshakova.
She also recalled that the president's order was not only for the HRC, but also for the Supreme Court (SC), which has not yet disclosed its proposals.
The time for the task to be completed by the Supreme Court (among the co-executors - the Prosecutor General's Office and the Russian Human Rights Commissioner) is still available.
To report to Vladimir Putin on how effectively the independence of justice is ensured in the Russian Federation, Supreme Court Chairman Vyacheslav Lebedev must report by September 1.
Living the high life: a half-story and clever design techniques have turned this small apartment in Earl's Court into a spacious residence
Joan Lee, a former banker with a passion for property repair, moved from a spacious house in Knightsbridge to an apartment in Earls Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the ground floor of a beautiful Queen Anne-style model home, and the new design is supported by the fact that Joan didn't pack up and move in again.
"I used to live with my ex in Knightsbridge, on a lot more land", Joan says.
I was looking for something that would match my money.
I was shown this apartment in Earl's Court, and it had the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered her a price that very day.
Since the first inspection, the 1,000-square-foot apartment has undergone a complete renovation.
It was originally a one-bedroom apartment with a complicated layout - to get to the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen - and Joanna wanted to add storage space and a half-story to make the most of the generous ceiling heights.
I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
"These were my demands", she says.
To this end, she hired Erfan Azadi from Notting Hill-based architecture and design studio Duck & Shed to use the 12.5-foot ceilings to create a dwelling that would not only be a successful project, but would also be fit for Joan to live in.
The ceiling was not high enough to allow two rooms to be placed one above the other, so the architectural challenge was to create a half-story where one could stand fully.
Erfan had to think creatively to cope with the briefing.
"Working with steel structures is very difficult", he explains.
We had to arrange the rooms so that they were on top of each other and didn't have to bend over.
Instead of simply building a simple platform, we had to bend the structure so that it was at the right height and allowed us to use the space above and below.
This solution allowed Erfan to create two full-size rooms one above the other in a designated space  and much more interesting.
From the upper half of the floor, a stained copper light window from the Retrouvius overlooks the luxurious living room below.
Mirrored furniture with gold finish, silver accents and vintage lighting fixtures by Serge Muay set the style of the project.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding spectacle, space and light.
The short corridor is framed with mirrors to make it seem longer.
In the kitchen, the mirrored security panel seems like a window to another room.
The mirrored cabinets in the entrance are for all Joan's dishes.
To create a sense of more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can be a wall around the kitchen when it's not being used.
There's nothing new about folding kitchens.
The unique thing about this kitchen is that it's a sliding up door, like a garage.
"It was an engineering feat", says Erfan, referring to the steel-reinforced wood-fibre shield door.
It's equipped with a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slides very easily.
Through a wise use of space and storage, Joan gained an additional 40 square feet [16 sq m], an extra bedroom, and an improved layout.
"After all, floor space is what you're going to sell, that is, what your property is valued at", says Erfan.
"Basically, the real estate agent will go in and do the calculations based on the floor area".
Here, they were able to increase the floor area using high-quality materials that add a touch of luxury to the space.
"The materials are what we touch, so they help create an emotional connection with the home", Erfan says.
No one falls in love with a power line in a wall.
It's important, but it doesn't touch the strings of our hearts.
It's a testament to the fact that with good design and a large footprint, an apartment can go from ordinary to something amazing.
In fact, like Joan, you may decide to stay.
