Italy is tightening its tone on NGO rescue ships.
Italy has warned NGOs that own rescue boats in the Mediterranean that they cannot continue their work unless they comply with new rules governing their activities.
"If NGOs do not comply with the new code of conduct, it is difficult to say whether they will be able to continue their activities", said Interior Minister Mario Minniti in an interview with the daily newspaper Stampa in Turin.
The warning came a day after Italian authorities seized a ship belonging to the German humanitarian organization Jugend Rettet on suspicion that its crew was actually cooperating with human traffickers and facilitating illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which has been in operation for just over a year, declined to comment on the substance of the detailed charges brought against it by Italian prosecutor Ambrogio Cartosio.
"Saving lives is and will remain our top priority, and we regret that we cannot continue our search and rescue efforts at this time", the organization said in a statement on social media.
"We can only evaluate all the charges that have been made now "after we have gathered all the information and can assess the situation".
Italian authorities have been monitoring the Juventus, owned by the "Jugend Rettet", since October.
His crew is suspected of taking in entire lifeboats, which were then sent directly to them by traffickers, and allowing smugglers to leave with boats they could reuse.
At least one such meeting is believed to have taken place just 1.3 miles from the Libyan coast, according to the indictment, the contents of which were published in Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the orders of the Italian coastguard, who oversee rescue operations in the area, more out of humanitarian zeal than any other motive.
The code of conduct essentially requires that ships like the Juvenet have an Italian police officer on board to monitor their activities.
So far, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have agreed to abide by the code: Save the Children, Malta's MOAS and Pro-Activa Open Arms from Spain.
The latter said on Thursday that it considered the new rules unnecessary but acceptable as long as they did not cause any "significant changes or disruptions" to its rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign the declaration was the Nobel Prize-winning organization Médecins Sans Frontières (MSF).
