"In Libya, we don't want to be associated with any side of the conflict"
The Russian authorities have recently significantly intensified their policy towards Libya, and the delegations of the warring Libyan parties have visited Moscow.
The head of the Russian contact group for the intra-Lybia settlement at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation and the State Duma, the assistant of the head of the Chechen Republic Lev Denigov told "Ъ" what goals Moscow pursues in this region and on whom it is betting.
The Libya Contact Group you lead is a little-known entity.
Let's say, the contact group on Ukraine - everybody knows about it.
And here, the veil of secrecy.
What exactly do you do, what are your goals?
The contact group was established on the initiative of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation and the State Duma.
Its activities are supervised by Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delimkhanov (Duma deputy from Chechnya. - "Ъ").
The latter is authorized to work on the Libyan direction by the Speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
The impetus for the creation of the group was the detention in Libya of the Russian tanker "Mehanik Chebotarev" (in September 2015, there were 11 people on board. - "Ъ").
We were thinking about how to help the crew.
Then a contact group was created from military experts, representatives of the State Duma, our work was supported by the head of Chechnya Ramzan Kadyrov.
How did you end up running it?
Since I've been working in Libya since 2008, I was asked to lead the group's work.
Our activities were not limited to the liberation of the sailors from the "Mechanics of Chebotarev".
We managed to establish contacts with representatives of all the main factions that are opposed to each other in the Libyan conflict - both from Tripoli (where the UN-recognized government headed by Faiz Sarraj is based. - "K" -), and from Tobruk (the parliament residence that opposes the government and supports Marshal Khalifa Haftar, who controls the eastern regions of Libya. - "K").
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metig (Vice Prime Minister of Libya - "Ъ"), we were able to quickly agree on the release of Russian sailors.
So we decided to use these contacts more effectively, to create a contact group.
Its task is to analyse the situation, identify the key factors and players, and dialogue with all parties to the conflict.
I want to emphasize: in Libya we do not want to associate ourselves with any of the parties to the conflict, we are in dialogue with all.
How many people are in the contact group and how many of them are in Libya on a permanent basis?
There are five people in the contact group now.
Some of them have experience in law enforcement, including the Department of Defense.
We also want to bring in a group of regional experts, representatives from the Middle East Institute of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
None of our staff are in Libya permanently, there's no need for that yet.
Are there any Russian military advisors, instructors in Libya now?
And if so, whose side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All the talk and publicity about it is not true.
But your contact group is made up of ex-military...
Yes, and their presence is necessary.
Like when we visit hot spots.
Or the cities that were closed to us until a certain point, like Misrata (where militia units based, which played a role in the overthrow of Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in 2011 and became noticeably active in the following years. - "Kommersant").
We arrived in Misurata in January of this year.
We were scared, they said that it was all Islamists, terrorists.
But it was important for us to assess the situation there, to analyze the real military potential, who is responsible for what, why there are rumors, what is the real role of Islamists there.
In Misrata, we met with all the representatives of the detachments that were engaged in the destruction of ISIS in Sirte (in December 2016, this city on the Mediterranean coast was recaptured from the militants of the "Islamic State" - "Ъ" banned in Russia).
We wanted to look at them, meet these people, check the information that they were the ones who played a crucial role in the destruction of ISIS in Libya, not Khalifa Haftar, who claimed the credit.
And what conclusion did you reach?
Haftar won the Islamic State in Libya?
He didn't do that.
Haftar was operating on another front, Benghazi.
And the IS in Sirte was fought by the Tripoli government.
And by the way, we invited the people who were running this counter-terrorism operation to Russia.
And they arrived - the visit lasted from April 19 to 23 this year, the Libyan delegation was received in the Federation Council, in the Duma, the Foreign Ministry and Rosgvardiya.
You've been to all the regions of Libya, we understand, and you probably have an idea of the mood of the local elites and field commanders.
Do you think that the ceasefire, the elections, that were agreed by Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Sarraj in Paris at the end of July, will be implemented?
Or will the treaties be broken, as has happened many times in the past, with fighting resuming, with the parties trying to take power alone?
The good news is that Sarge and Haftar have agreed to meet again, which was impossible not long ago.
In the recent past, both leaders have been very negative about each other.
As for the Russian position...
It is often written and said that Moscow actively supports Haftar, and many believe it.
We encountered this situation when we were in Misurata, and Haftar was boarding the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov on that very day.
It was a coincidence.
But in Misurata, they didn't believe in coincidence.
We were told, "You must be very brave people to come to us today".
But our job is to show that we are not only supporting Haftar, we are engaging in dialogue with all the key players in the Libyan conflict.
You and Haftar have been in contact.
Does the fact that he studied twice in the USSR make it easier to understand Russian partners on a human, emotional level?
And by the way, does Haftar speak Russian?
Russian he knows, very relative.
But the fact that he's been studying with us, of course, makes it easier to talk to him.
And not just him, by the way.
When we talk to the military in Tripoli and Misurata, we meet generals who studied in Russia or in the Soviet Union.
And they speak Russian very well.
And they're drawn to Russia, they're somewhat nostalgic for Russia.
Do you think it is likely that the arms embargo on Libya will be lifted soon?
Are your Libyan contacts interested in Russian weapons supplies?
Yes, of course, but as I said, we are not taking sides in this conflict and we do not wish to arm one side against the other.
We'd like to see everyone in a more or less equal position.
As for the arms embargo, there are constant calls from the Libyan side for Russia to somehow facilitate its lifting.
Now Libya is actively moving towards the process of drafting a constitution.
We hope that the parties will reach a compromise, an internal consensus.
Then there's the elections, which was discussed at the meeting between Sarraja and Haftar.
If elections are held and a legitimate government is finally elected (and currently neither side has such a status), the UN Security Council can be asked to lift the arms embargo.
To raise this issue now is pointless and dangerous, it will only lead to an escalation of the conflict.
The media reported that Italy, faced with the problem of African refugees sailing from Libya, feels abandoned by its EU allies.
Could Moscow in this situation help Italian partners by using its ties to the Libyans?
How realistic is it, for example, that Haftar's troops will take control of the coast and end the smuggling business that transports immigrants to Europe?
That's a very timely question.
We're working on it.
The Italians need Russian support because Moscow is in dialogue with Haftar, with Saraj, with Misurata and with the south of the country.
And the tribes in southern Libya are playing a big role in this, and they are willing to cooperate with Russia.
Is this about the southerners stopping the flow of migrants at the far reaches?
So, basically, they were turning back the buses that were carrying Nigerian migrants?
We're working on it.
But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups have an interest in keeping these flows going.
We hope to help bring the southerners together in a negotiation process between Sarj, Haftar and the tribes in the south.
But first we'd like to see a consensus on this issue between Haftar and Sarajem.
The head of the government in Tripoli, Faiz Sarraj, is considered an Islamist, a supporter of the introduction of the norms of the Sharia in the country.
How radical is his view?
Would that be a barrier to building relations with Russia or the West?
I'll give you my personal opinion of him.
In my opinion, he is, on the contrary, an opponent of radical Islam.
But there are Islamists in his coalition.
Yes, but he himself maintains that Libya should be a perfectly normal country - moderately Islamic, open to the world.
And he's also actively fighting terrorists.
How did he get such a reputation?
It was created by countries that are not interested in Russia's interaction with Tripoli.
Tripoli is the capital, the seat of the legislative, executive and judicial powers.
There's the national oil corporation, the national bank and other government agencies.
Of course, some countries had an interest in keeping us out of it.
And we've been playing them all over the map and actively communicating with both Tripoli and Tobruk.
And we're already seeing the fruits of this work: Rosneft has signed a cooperation agreement with the state oil company of Libya - NOC.
The director of the NOC, Mustafa Sanalla, with whom the head of Rosneft, Igor Sechin, made a deal, is himself directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago, the first shipment of Libyan oil was made by Rosneft.
What will Russia do with it?
I guess that's a sell-off.
What other economic interests does Russia have in Libya?
He plans to re-sign the contracts made under Muammar Gaddafi.
This includes previous agreements in the transport sector (railway construction), energy sector (electrification) and a number of other areas.
Do the Libyans have enough to pay?
Well, they have oil.
So, like the Iran deal, this is an oil-for-services deal?
I don't know what the pattern is, because I'm not directly involved in these issues.
Actually, the economy is not the most important thing for Russia in Libya.
We're basically doing peacekeeping work there.
Our main objective is to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans to reach an agreement with each other, so that they can establish order in their own country and Libya ceases to be a favorable environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, this is the main task - to help the Libyan people and to push the terrorists out of there.
Do you have any information on the presence in Libya (now or previously) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to find out.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that to date there are no Russians or other former Soviet citizens there.
He said he had about 50 thousand phone records of representatives of Islamist and radical groups (in Libya. - "Ъ") and Russian speech does not sound there.
What country are these fighters from?
I wouldn't want to go into those details.
Then let's put it this way.
How many Libyan Islamist militants are Libyans themselves?
There are hardly any Libyans among them, less than 5%.
The rest are just newbies.
Can Moscow conduct intra-Libyan negotiations following the example of Paris?
There are plans.
We are actively negotiating with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow, and have expressed their readiness to come to Moscow or Grozny.
When can we have these talks?
It's hard to tell right now.
There are still a few visits to be made, and then I hope that there will be clarity about the time and place of the talks.
