The sentencing of Michelle Carter for the messages that incited Conrad Roy to suicide
A Massachusetts woman was sentenced to two and a half years in prison for using text messages and phone calls to encourage her boyfriend, Conrad Roy, to commit suicide.
Michelle Carter, now 20, will serve 15 months of her sentence and another five years of probation.
Carter was found guilty in June of the manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy's father said at the hearing on Thursday, "My family is devastated.
My son was my best friend".
Carter was allowed to remain free pending appeal.
She faced a maximum sentence of 20 years, but her lawyers said both she and Roy were suffering from mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red trousers and a cream blouse, listened to the verdict standing with her hands clenched and her eyes down.
"By her actions, she killed Conrad Roy", the prosecutor told the court.
"She cut his life to make her own better.
She didn't take responsibility", she said.
"She showed no remorse".
But attorney Carter said it was "a tragic incident that she deeply regrets".
However, Judge Lawrence Monis said that in his opinion, her "age, level of maturity, or even mental illness did not significantly influence her actions".
The prosecutor read the statement of Roy's mother, Lynn Roy, which stated: "Not a day has gone by that I have not mourned the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and how I'm doing - I'm trying to support his sisters, despite all the pain that will stay with us forever", it says.
Roy's sister Camden Roy said she was haunted by the thought that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become an aunt to his children.
"To lose someone who has been with me since I was born is a pain that will stay with me for the rest of my life", she said.
This case is likely to set a legal precedent, as there is no law in Massachusetts that would hold a person responsible for advising a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in a car with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The case gained national attention when it was revealed that he had been driven to suicide by Carter's messages.
"You can hang yourself, jump off a roof, stab yourself I don't know there are many ways", she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death, when he was on vacation with his family.
A few minutes before she killed herself, she wrote, "You must do this, Conrad", and "You only need to turn on the lighter, and you will be free and happy".
Judge Moniz said that Carter wanted to get attention with Roy's death, and he banned her from talking to the press to stop her getting what she wanted.
Lawyers are divided on the issue.
One of the few to defend Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 of the murder of her British roommate in Italy and acquitted two years later.
Knox, 30, published a special opinion piece in the Los Angeles Times, which stated: "Michelle Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison".
