When astronomers first studied the properties of the stratosphere of a giant exoplanet called WASP-121b, they were surprised by its temperature, which is capable of vaporizing iron and other metals.
The researchers noted that the water molecules are heated by the starlight to the point that they emit infrared radiation.
The Hubble Space Telescope has captured the glow of water molecules on this gas giant: the high temperature causes the water in the planet's atmosphere to glow in the infrared.
WASP-121b is a hot Jupiter, a gas giant comparable in size and mass to the largest planet in the solar system, but located dozens of times closer to its parent star.
