Climate change is threatening the lavender in Provence.
It has become a symbol of Provence and Southern France, but there are now fears that it is threatened by climate change.
Lavender has been made to grow less well by the arid weather and disease-carrying insects; this has been a constant headache for scientists and farmers trying to find a solution.
Eric Chess, an expert at the CRIEPPAM agricultural research institute in Provence, says: "The lavender in Provence is really under threat because in recent years the plant has been feeling the effects of climate change: there has been a lot less rain in spring and especially in autumn.
It affects the life of the lavender.
And then there are the little cicadas, jumping on the leaves, the insects carrying the micro-bacteria; in very dry weather they become very numerous".
There's a lot at stake.
Lavender is not only a popular holiday oil; lavender oil is also used in perfumes and cosmetics.
Says Eric Schess: "Instead of very long stems with a large number of large flowers, we have small, underdeveloped, weakened or absent.
So we have fewer parts that contain essential oils".
Solutions being considered include improving water distribution and slowing evaporation from the soil, as well as spraying plants with a protective clay-water mixture and growing varieties that are more resistant to drought.
