The security experts wrote three words on a board hanging in the room: enemies, neutral people, allies.
They asked journalists to name names for each column - no proof needed, suspicion and gut feelings would suffice.
These are drug dealers, politicians, businessmen, journalists suspected of being held by the government or the cartels, a whole list of thugs who make it dangerous to report on the chaos in Mexico.
Violence is rampant, and the number of dead bodies in the country is growing: according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, at least 25 journalists have been killed since President Enrico Pena Nieto took office in December 2012; 589 people have been placed under federal protection following attacks and threats; and at least seven people have been killed in seven states this year.
Among the latter is their publisher and inspirer, co-founder of "Rio de Janeiro" Javier Valdes Cardenas.
"The biggest mistake is to live in Mexico and be a journalist", Valdes wrote in one of his many books on violent crime related to drugs.
