The dinosaur used camouflage to avoid its enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, albeit a terrifying one.
The researchers said the first fossil of an incredible rhino-sized creature, discovered by a Canadian miner, was so well preserved that experts called it "the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs".
It was so well preserved that they could even identify that the color of his scaly skin was reddish-brown and say that he had, in some way, a dark past.
In a report published in the journal Modern Biology, it was described as "the best-preserved Tyrrhophorus ever found and one of the best examples of a dinosaur in the world".
This fossil is a recently discovered specimen of a Nodosaurus that lived in the middle Cretaceous, between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
Its incredibly good condition has astonished researchers who call it "really remarkable".
This herbivorous thyreophore is the best-preserved fossil of its kind in the history of the find, according to National Geographic magazine.
It was found by Sean Funk while he was working at the Millennium Mine of the Sancor Company near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
He came across something that seemed different from the surrounding breed and decided to look closer.
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
For the next six years, work was underway to find the animal in the 2,500-foot-thick (11,100-kilogram) earthen floor.
Now that all the hard work is done, the finished product can be demonstrated.
"A slight snoring can make you believe it's sleeping", said lead author Caleb Brown, a research fellow at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology, where the creature is on display.
It will go down in history as one of the most beautiful and best preserved examples of a dinosaur The Mona Lisa of the dinosaurs.
By studying its skin, researchers found that this herbivorous creature, despite being shelled and resembling a walking tank, was apparently at considerable risk from carnivorous dinosaurs.
This powerful-shell dinosaur used red-and-white camouflage to hide from predators, and it employed a defensive technique known as protective coloration, which many animals today also use.
This would have allowed it to blend in with its surroundings more quickly and avoid encounters with enemies, experts say, suggesting that it was preyed upon by larger dinosaurs.
This 110-million-year-old creature, a member of the family Nodozaurs, was widely reported in the press in May, and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
Scientists have already studied the animal and named it Borealopelta markmitchelli after the museum's lab technician Mark Mitchell, one of the team members who spent over 7,000 hours on its painstaking excavation.
The extraordinary preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of the scales and armor plates on its body.
They found a protective coating, a common method of protection in the animal kingdom, which means that the top of the creature was darker than its underside.
Although the protective coloration is well-established, the discovery was a surprise because the size of the Borealopelta dinosaur far exceeds the size of any currently living protective-colored animal.
It's possible that this dinosaur was so actively hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution chose to mask confrontation as a means of survival.
But most modern animals with protective coloration - such as deer, zebra, or armadillo - are much smaller and more accessible to prey, suggesting that the Nodo had to fight hard to survive.
"The serious threat from predators to a massive, heavily armored dinosaur shows just how dangerous the Cretaceous predatory dinosaurs were", Brown said.
Chemical analysis of organic compounds in the dinosaur's scales also suggests that its skin must have been reddish-brown.
Scientists are continuing to study the animal, looking for clues about its life, including preserved digestive tracts, to determine what it ate during its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into a river and was carried away to the sea, where it sank and lay backwards on the ocean floor.
At that time, Alberta was as warm as southern Florida is today, and rivers and oceans likely extended much farther inland than they do now.
"This is a truly remarkable Nodosaur, completely covered in its preserved scaled skin, yet fully preserved in three dimensions, preserving the original shape of the animal", said Brown.
As a result, the animal now looks almost exactly as it did in the Early Cretaceous.
You don't have to use your imagination to recreate it, just a slight squint and you can practically believe it's asleep.
The Cretaceous is the era when giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs that stood on two legs, roamed the Earth.
Although the most remarkable of them, Tyrannosaurus rex, lived millions of years later than the Borealopelta, the Thyreophora may have been hunted by one of its formidable ancestors.
Among them is the acrocanthosaurus, a monster measuring 11 and a half meters long and weighing six tons.
Scientists, whose recent findings are published in the journal Modern Biology, believe that Borealopelta was carried away after death into the sea and mummified in an eel.
The entity was discovered by Sean Funk while working in the Millenium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
Museum officials report that this is the best-preserved thyroid in the world, along with the skin and shell, and it's intact, from the snout to the femur.
These creatures averaged about 18 feet (five meters) in length and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1300 kilograms).
Their distinctive feature was two twenty-inch spines protruding from the shoulders.
Researchers believe that this herbivorous thyreophore struggled to cross what is now Canada until a flooded river washed it out to sea.
But the dinosaur's underwater burial preserved its shell with precision down to the smallest detail.
The fossil remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the remains of the skin still cover the greyish shell plates along the dinosaur's skull.
As Michael Gresco wrote in a National Geographic article, such a degree of safety is "as rare as winning the lottery".
The longer I look at it, the more amazing it seems.
The fossilized remains of the skin are still covered by the wrinkled armor plates that line the animal's skull.
His right front leg is extended along the side, five toes on it are turned up.
I can count the scales on his feet.
