The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called "The Emergence of Similarity".
It's the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Harborough, whose art combines technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transgender woman and prominent dissident whose sentence Barack Obama commuted just three days before the end of his presidency.
By analyzing with a computer program the DNA that Manning had obtained and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of the faces that people with this genome might have, Dewey-Harburg created a profound, though difficult to grasp, manifesto that focuses not only on the plasticity of DNA data - the different ways in which it can be interpreted and the inherent determinism of these interpretations - but also on the notion of identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward but has openly identified as a woman since her teenage years, was convicted in 2013 on 20 counts, including six counts of violating the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
Her photos in prison were not available, so only one of her photographs was known: a grainy black-and-white selfie of Manning in a platinum-tinted wig, clearly feeling awkward at the wheel of a car; this is the photograph she came to be associated with.
In 2015, Dewey-Harborg successfully completed her 2012 project "Visions of Strangers".
In it, she created portraits of unknown people using forensic evidence like cigarettes and chewing gum, extracting DNA from this garbage and creating images of what these people might have looked like.
And then she got an email from Paper Magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted a portrait to illustrate the article", Dewey-Hagborg explained at a preview of the new exhibition for the press.
Chelsea was not allowed to visit or be photographed at the time, so they contacted her and asked if she would like to have a portrait created from her DNA.
In an unusual way, the artist and her prison muse became friends by correspondence, and exchanged several letters over the course of two years.
They even wrote a comic book, "Repressed Images", illustrated by Shoyle Canoung, which depicted how in the future the president would commute Chelsea's sentence so she could visit the exhibition in person.
That Obama did decide to release Manning just days after the book was published was a pleasant surprise after seven years of hard labor in a military prison in Kansas.
There's something deep and powerful about the fact that this exhibition is opening just as Donald Trump is waging war on people who leak government secrets and inventing new ways to fuel the animosity on Twitter that he's supposed to be softening.
When Dewey-Harborough was asked about the coincidence of all this, she said, "Nothing happens by chance".
In the artist's statement, written on the gallery wall, Manning's huge signature at the bottom (with a heart instead of the dot over the "i" in her last name) calls for an end to "automatic segregation based on gender, race, sexual orientation and culture".
On the opposite side is her mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar of C, G, and A pencils.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, as the artist scientifically put it), Dewey-Harborough hoped to show how we are all remarkably similar, at least in our biological makeup.
"I hope to explain to people that our genome does not determine what we are, how open the genetic data is to interpretation and how subjective it is", said Dewey-Harborg, whose 2007 video work "False Memories" is also on display here.
"DNA data can tell us a lot of different stories, and 30 of those stories are here".
The last part of the exhibition that fits in one room is the aforementioned comic book.
It shows Manning in King Kong style, standing over the U.S. Correctional Building with a speaker in his hand.
"If they kill your speech, they win", it says.
"So never shut up".
"This is a direct quote from a letter she wrote to me", says the artist, greeting us from Philadelphia.
"I still get the chills when I talk about it".
Manning hasn't seen the exhibit in person -- as it was divinely portrayed in the comics -- but when she does, she'll be greeted by masks in the center of the room, her own genomic simulacres, gathered like a crowd of protesters.
This is also done intentionally, as is everything in the exhibition up to the height (5"2, Manning's height), on which the genetic haplogroups were drawn in pencil.
"I used to hang them on the walls, but now I wanted them to look like a crowd of people", says Dewey-Harborg of the portraits.
"I wanted them to be like the mass movement that had formed around Chelsea, like the movement that stood for its liberation".
