Startups that will help your company not become the next Uber.
E. Hermire wanted to measure employee satisfaction at her e-commerce startup, but the surveys didn't work.
The answers were often vague, useless, or worse, insincere.
And even though she promised anonymity, some employees didn't trust the process.
"He was never consistent or objective", said Errett, who runs the San Francisco-based e-commerce hair care company Madison Reed, which employs 75 people.
So she turned to third parties for help.
There's a new kind of HR startup that's emerging that helps companies figure out how their employees are doing.
By developing and licensing software that measures employee engagement, they allow companies to do express interviews, reach out to specific teams and demographics, offer employees anonymity and a hotline for complaints, and in some cases allow whistleblowers to bypass top management and reach out directly to the board.
"Now we have tools like Strava and Fitbit to monitor health, where's Fitbit for your company?" says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of Redwood City-based startup Glint, whose analytics software is used by companies to measure engagement.
Errett said that she gained a better understanding of what her employees think and feel after three years of using Glint.
In addition to express surveys and surveys of specific teams, the product offers a company heat map and visually displays which departments have more complaints and which managers have lower approval ratings, allowing her to understand why.
Companies are slowly realizing that they need to control their workplace environment, or they will become another "Uber" who got caught up in a scandal when a former employee posted a blog post describing an aggressive environment in which those who expressed dissatisfaction were punished.
For startups like Glint, this desire to control is a lucrative business opportunity.
The financial technology-focused payments-speak-together.com estimates that the global governance, regulation and compliance industry could be worth over $118.7 billion by 2020.
Denver, Colorado-based startup Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, saw a small surge in interest and activity earlier this year amid a decline in Uber's reputation.
Convercent has nearly 600 clients, including Airbnb, Microsoft, and Tesla.
Recently, Uber has been making a splash in the customer base.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customized employee opinion surveys, collect confidential responses in real time, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides an anonymous text message hotline that allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if it's a top manager, complaints go straight to the board.
"The court of public opinion has taken over the power of the inspectors", said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If a company is found to be misbehaving or unethical, even if inspectors do not intervene, the company could face costly consequences in the form of customer boycotts, employee departures and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain with more than 25,000 employees across 500 locations, has used Convercent for over a year to ensure that employees are aware of the rules and procedures and to offer a simple way to contact the company's head office.
Before, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she had to look up the phone number or the email address of the head office, file a formal complaint, and hope that it would be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and embarrassing experience, said James Vitrano, head of legal at Ruby Tuesday, who said there was no normal way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company is using Convercent, issues that were previously hidden from managers in offices in other cities or states  such as discrimination, harassment and unfair pay  can be detected and addressed more quickly.
"I can get closer to a holistic, all-round understanding of the employee situation", said Vitraño, who heads the Ruby Tuesday network's risk management group.
And we protect our shareholders from employee lawsuits.
According to Queensland, companies began to take ethics, values and employee engagement more seriously in 2002, after the accounting firm Arthur Andersen went bankrupt due to ethical violations in the Enron deal.
But it wasn't until social media became popular that companies realized they couldn't keep their dirty laundry from going viral online.
"Before people started using technology to control their ethics, they used hope as a strategy", he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, charging companies a regular fee to use their products.
It's a business model and opportunity that has been embraced by venture capitalists who have backed both startups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million in funding from firms such as Sapphire Ventures and Mola Capital, bringing the total capital of the company to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing the company's total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising, given the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
A growing body of research demonstrates that today's employees expect more from their jobs than they did in the past.
In highly competitive markets like Silicon Valley, high wages and exciting projects are just the bare minimum.
Employees want to feel accepted and valued, and that they are giving their time to a company with a positive mission.
"When people are happy to work for a company, feel heard, and see the work they do as producing results, they are more likely to make the company a success", says Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee satisfaction at LinkedIn, which uses both Convercent and Glint.
Investors make money when the companies in their portfolio do well; companies do well when their employees are committed and engaged.
If third-party analytics tools promise to increase employee loyalty and engagement, it's no surprise that they're finding support.
According to experts in workplace culture, it is important to have data on employee engagement.
But that data is useless until the company's trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks for feedback from employees, it can create the impression that change is coming.
And if change doesn't come fast enough, or doesn't come at all, frustration can develop, and employees lose interest.
"If you're going to ask for 4,000 proposals, you have to be prepared to have 4,000 conversations", says Russell Rath, president of management consulting at Kotter International, who has seen companies make the mistake of relying too much on data collection.
Because if you don't go all the way, the staff will wonder, "Did you really hear me?"
Do you care?
If you don't care, why shouldn't I?
According to Earrett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, is able to take action the same day someone reports a problem using Glint.
And after gathering feedback from employees who were unhappy with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve the problems.
The company Ruby Tuesday is gaining new knowledge about its employees and hopes that in the long term, this knowledge will help it to retain employees more effectively in an industry known for high turnover.
"If you don't try to create a culture of transparency, you will lose people", said Vitrano.
If you lose people, you lose clients.
And if you lose customers, you lose companies.
