To create a comic novel: One Castle in English History
In the recent past, the tiny Scotney Castle was featured in the music video "Squeeze", and in the '70s and '80s it served as a retreat for Margaret Thatcher.
But 700 years ago, from his comfortable hideaway in the valley of the River Beal in Kent, he watched the turbulent history around him, and now inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshire-haired man with a penchant for historical documents, to write a comic novel.
"I think it's so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago", he enthuses.
"You feel it so personally when you hold this letter in your hand".
The Castle in England covers the period from the Middle Ages to the Evardian era and tells the stories of the families who lived in Scotney; each story is illustrated by one of the young British artists - Isaac Lenkewich, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
This is not the first book by Rhodes to be based on archival data: in 2014, he wrote "Dead Man's Teeth and Other Stories", a collection of materials from the British Library's archives; this project unexpectedly touched him to the core.
"I could have been disfigured by a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a Jacobite double agent", he says.
"This is his fingerprint".
And the letters always smell of smoke, because in those days, they lit fires for light.
And 300 years in the future, you feel like you're there, too.
Oh, how I love the archives!"
For a man so obsessed with old papers, to receive support from the National Trust and the Arts Council of England and to live in a castle for four months ("I've been there a little, to be honest") seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent days studying the "new" Victorian castle, going through the archives and looking at the estate's many treasures and antiques - such as the hyena heads on the walls or bottles that had been in the moat for centuries.
He walked through the park and the ruins of the old castle, talking to the foresters, gardeners and sometimes the artists who worked on the illustrations for his book.
Then at night he would "drink whiskey and sit down to write".
The history of Scotney Castle is not well documented, as the National Trust only gained full access to it in 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hassey, died.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the staff had just begun to process the archives, which he describes as "something that aristocrats have been dumping in the attic for centuries".
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps of who owned what: "You think land disputes are boring", says Rhodes, "but there were two families fighting over this birch.
It happens, guys!"
In some of the stories, the castle becomes the starting point for a wider exploration of English history: for example, in The Worker, the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasants' Revolt of 1381.
"There is a reference to a rebellion that took place in the castle in 1380, in a book called 'The Knights of the Houses of Kent and Sussex,'" says Rhodes.
"The peasant revolt had begun in these places, and I thought that a revolt was a suitable beginning.
Maybe they were connected?"
Other stories are strongly connected to the castle's history - for example, The Priest, which tells of a Jesuit priest who was kept by the Darrel family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or "The Smuggler", about 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell, who is believed to have staged his own funeral by piling up the coffin with stones (this was discovered years later when the coffin was dug up).
The Darrelas were the Rhodes family's favorite of all the Scotney inhabitants: "The gentlemen seem to have been the perfect swindlers, always going into debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
"Darrel men have, for generations, "solved their debt problems by marrying rich older women, "who I imagine as a company of nice guys "who can take care of the heirs of large fortunes".
After completing her work at the castle, Rhodes looks for other opportunities to gain a unique writing experience.
He spent two weeks in the Finnish wilderness, writing a graphic novel about Elamyanmäki, a place that was a sanatorium in the early 20th century, and then became forest again.
But Scotney remains a special place to him.
"I was sad to leave", he says.
"I felt like, 'Fuck, I need to get back to real life.'"
