I think we're all so stressed out that we're about to burst.
Less is said about Trump's ability to bring families together.
I'm writing this because my cousin, a left-wing poet from Chicago who's had a long run of Republican feuds in her family, came to see me in New York this week.
She reminded me that uniting against a common enemy can have a powerful effect.
With Trump in the White House, everyone she knows, including the Republican brother she's been arguing with about politics for decades, suddenly and strangely found themselves on the same side.
After dinner, it's certainly good; but I can't help thinking that in the larger context it can be quite dangerous.
Trump has reinforced the left, but the deforming effect of his rule could shift us all to the right.
When we talk about Trump and "normalization", we mean the unlikely possibility that one day we will no longer be amazed by his antics.
There is, however, a more dubious scenario in which Trump normalizes right-wing Republicans who, against his standards, suddenly appear to be a model of common sense.
I found myself missing a lot of old-fashioned Mitt Romney craziness today - with a dog on the roof of his car and a 14 percent income tax (but at least we knew what his tax return looked like) - and compared to Trump, both seem like very little evil.
