Red meat, dairy, and chocolate can help alleviate BPH.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent studies suggest the opposite: A diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products may help to alleviate the symptoms of those suffering from inflammatory bowel disease.
This incurable disease, which affects an estimated 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, causes colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhoea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
While patients are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy products to ease symptoms, researchers at the University of Washington have found that the key amino acid protein tryptophan promotes the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
Dr. Marco Colonna, the lead researcher, explained that the immune cells in the intestines keep harmful microbes from entering the body.
Cells that can trigger the inflammation are balanced by cells that can increase tolerance, protecting the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too much distorted towards inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel disease.
Experiments have shown that mice that have a certain bacterium in their intestines have a tolerance cell.
And this bacterium needs tryptophan, one of the building blocks of protein, to start these cells.
Professor Kolonna said: "We have established a link between a species of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - that is part of the normal gut microbiome and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice ate, the more of these immune cells they had".
He suggested that the same would work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet could promote a more tolerant and less inflammatory environment in the gut.
Dr. Luisa Servantes-Barragans, studying a variety of immune cells that promote tolerance, discovered that one group of mice had these cells, while another group, which belonged to the same line but was kept separate, did not.
She hypothesized that the difference might be caused by the microbiomes of the mouse gut - communities of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the mouse intestinal cells was sequenced, and they found six different kinds of bacteria that were present in the mice that had immune cells, but not in the mice that didn't have immune cells.
Mice that were raised in a sterile environment, that didn't have a good microbiome and didn't develop this type of immune cell, got L. reuteri, and they had immune cells.
To understand how the bacteria affect the immune system, researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid environment and then transferred small portions of the liquid - free of bacteria - to immature immune cells isolated from mice.
The immune cells have mutated into cells that increase tolerance.
When the active ingredient was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a byproduct of the tryptophan processing, known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's diet, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the tryptophan level was reduced by half, the number of cells also dropped by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that humans have the same tolerance-enhancing cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether L. reuteri's tryptophan byproducts promote cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but in people suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases, defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found.
She says, "Perhaps we need to increase the growth of these cells, because they are the ones that control inflammation on the inside surface of the intestine.
High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri could potentially lead to an expansion of their population".
