A prop for the White House cost the taxpayer thousands of dollars.
According to military records provided to TIME magazine, the White House's decision last month to fly a Marine helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to American manufacturing cost taxpayers as much as $24,000.
The white-and-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as the Marine One when the president is on board, was the centerpiece of a July 17 event at the White House to showcase American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials inspected tech products from all 50 states.
The helicopter, made in Connecticut, was displayed alongside a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a truck from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Marine Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the unit responsible for helicopter operations, the White House Military Office ordered the helicopter's presence in a private order, or FRAGO, just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of an unusual event.
"I just wanted to make sure you were aware because this is an unusual media event", wrote the HMX-1 commander in an email to his superior, the Marine Corps' first deputy chief of air staff, the day before the event.
The letter stated that the helicopter would arrive at the South Lawn at approximately 7 a.m. on July 17 for the 3 p.m. event and would remain there until the lawn was cleared between 6 and 9 p.m. that same day.
The letter adds that if the White House departure is delayed, a second crew will be needed for the return flight in accordance with the hours of operation.
The first crew escorted the helicopter during the event, and the unit's security personnel stayed close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
It's unclear from the records obtained by TIME whether a second crew was eventually required.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 asked if the event was in violation of this order.
"Among other things, we asked if this was a violation of the Hatch Act, and we were told that it was not", the commander wrote.
"You don't seem to have anywhere to go", replied the deputy chief.
The Made in America event was declared an official event by the White House, and it was not covered by the Hatch Act.
But even formal events have political overtones.
During the event, the president made efforts to promote health care reform, which was then being worked on in the Senate, and praised the attempts to regulate governmental regulations.
The use of the aircraft known as Marine One and Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are supposed to use them for travel.
But to ask them for the sake of the photo opportunity is unusual.
Trump was already the subject of controversy in February when the presidential plane was passed in the background during his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was flooded with complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessor.
"The White House is excited about the Made in America show, which showcased products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials", said Deputy White House Press Secretary Lindsey Walters.
HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around the Washington metropolitan area and on the South Lawn to practice transporting the President of the United States to the White House with precision to the inch.
When Trump was in Germany for the G-20 summit in early July, the HMX-1 made 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight made for the "Made in America" event was counted against the crew's required training flights for the month.
The unit's helicopters also flew 11 extra hours that day as part of a "non-presidential support mission".
The White House says the taxpayers didn't pay for any of the other exhibits on display at the event.
A Sikorsky spokesman said the company was not involved in organizing a helicopter demonstration on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep a budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to the Department of Defense hourly rates for fiscal year 2017, the Department of Defense reimbursement rate for the VH-3D is $24,380 per hour of flight.
The unit records indicate that the aircraft's flight time was 30 minutes each way from its home base at Marine Corps Air Station Quantico in Virginia.
The White House claims the actual cost of operating a helicopter is well below that rate.
"It is a total mistake to calculate the cost to taxpayers based on a rough recovery rate", says Walters.
These sample rates include staff, maintenance and many other irreversible costs, which are included in the annual appropriations.
According to a 2015 study by the RAND Corporation, the reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but do take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and contract costs.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of a helicopter for the event.
"The idea is to showcase things made in America this week", Spicer said.
And I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut take great pride in the fact that they're contributing to national security, and that there are, I'm guessing, hundreds, if not thousands of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, we're all very proud of this helicopter and all the other military hardware that so many Americans have worked so hard to create.
So, of course, it's perfectly appropriate to draw attention to it.
It was unclear whether Trump interacted with the helicopter while inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he was definitely in the driver's seat of the fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed the Sikorsky company, joking with the press about his own fleet of products.
"I know Sikorsky very well", the president said. "I have three of them".
